---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Aetna International in Mexico', level: 2 },
  { id: 'us-coverage', text: 'US Coverage Advantage', level: 2 },
  { id: 'mexico-network', text: 'Network Coverage in Mexico', level: 2 },
  { id: 'plans-and-pricing', text: 'Plans and Pricing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'vs-local-options', text: 'vs Mexican Insurers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'imss-combo', text: 'IMSS + Aetna Strategy', level: 2 },
  { id: 'who-its-for', text: 'Who Should Choose Aetna', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Health Insurance in Mexico', href: '/countries/mexico/insurance' },
  { title: 'Aetna International Review', href: '/providers/aetna-international' },
  { title: 'Aetna vs GeoBlue', href: '/compare/aetna-international-vs-geoblue' },
];

const planColumns = [
  { key: 'plan', header: 'Plan' },
  { key: 'coverage', header: 'Coverage' },
  { key: 'mexicoPrice', header: 'Mexico (Age 35)' },
  { key: 'usIncluded', header: 'US Coverage' },
];

const planRows = [
  { plan: 'Pioneer', coverage: 'Inpatient + Emergency', mexicoPrice: '$130-175/mo', usIncluded: 'Full integrated' },
  { plan: 'Pioneer Prime', coverage: 'Inpatient + Outpatient', mexicoPrice: '$175-240/mo', usIncluded: 'Full integrated' },
  { plan: 'Pioneer Platinum', coverage: 'Comprehensive', mexicoPrice: '$240-320/mo', usIncluded: 'Full integrated' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'factor', header: 'Factor' },
  { key: 'aetna', header: 'Aetna International' },
  { key: 'mexican', header: 'Mexican Insurers' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { factor: 'Monthly Cost (Age 35)', aetna: '$175-240', mexican: '$120-180' },
  { factor: 'US Coverage', aetna: 'Full Aetna network', mexican: 'Not available' },
  { factor: 'Network in Mexico', aetna: 'Good', mexican: 'Extensive' },
  { factor: 'Deductible Type', aetna: 'Annual', mexican: 'Per-illness (lifetime)' },
  { factor: 'Currency', aetna: 'USD', mexican: 'MXN' },
  { factor: 'Medical Evacuation', aetna: 'Included', mexican: 'Usually not' },
  { factor: 'Medicare Replacement', aetna: 'Yes (abroad)', mexican: 'No' },
  { factor: 'Portability', aetna: 'Worldwide', mexican: 'Mexico only' },
];

const hospitalColumns = [
  { key: 'city', header: 'City' },
  { key: 'hospitals', header: 'Network Hospitals' },
  { key: 'directBilling', header: 'Direct Billing' },
];

const hospitalRows = [
  { city: 'Mexico City', hospitals: 'Hospital ABC, Médica Sur, Hospital Ángeles', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Guadalajara', hospitals: 'Hospital San Javier, Hospital Country 2000', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Monterrey', hospitals: 'Christus Muguerza, Hospital San José', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Puerto Vallarta', hospitals: 'Hospital CMQ, Hospiten', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Cancún', hospitals: 'Hospiten Cancún, Galenia Hospital', directBilling: true },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Aetna International Health Insurance in Mexico"
  description="Guide to using Aetna International in Mexico. Best for US expats needing Medicare replacement and full US network access. Pricing, network, and comparisons."
  headline="Aetna International Health Insurance in Mexico"
  subheadline="The smart choice for American expats. Full Aetna US network access built in—no surprise premiums when you visit family or need US specialists."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/mexico-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get an Aetna Mexico Quote"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/aetna-international"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Aetna International in Mexico</h2>
  <p>
    Mexico is the #1 destination for American retirees, and Aetna International is built for exactly this scenario. Unlike most international insurers that charge 40-60% extra for US coverage, Aetna includes US network access in all plans—because they know American expats visit family and sometimes need US specialists.
  </p>
  <p>
    Since Medicare doesn't cover you outside the US, Aetna International effectively replaces Medicare abroad while giving you the Aetna network when you're stateside.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">1.7M+</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Providers (US + intl)</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">Full</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">US network included</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">24/7</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">English support</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Get a Mexico-Specific Quote"
    description="See what Aetna International costs for US expats in Mexico."
    buttonText="Get Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/aetna-international"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="us-coverage">US Coverage Advantage</h2>
  <p>
    The biggest advantage of Aetna for Mexico expats is built-in US coverage. Here's why that matters:
  </p>

  <h3>Medicare Doesn't Work in Mexico</h3>
  <p>
    US Medicare generally doesn't cover healthcare outside the United States. If you're a US retiree in Mexico, you need separate coverage. Aetna provides that—and covers you when you return to the US.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mb-2">Cross-Border Example</h3>
    <p class="text-green-800">
      Living in Lake Chapala? With Aetna International, you can see your specialist in Guadalajara, get follow-up care in Phoenix when visiting your kids, and fly to Houston for a second opinion on a major surgery—all on the same policy with seamless coverage.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>How US Coverage Works</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Full access to Aetna's US network (1M+ providers)</li>
    <li>Same benefits in Mexico and the US</li>
    <li>Direct billing at major US hospitals</li>
    <li>No separate travel insurance needed for US trips</li>
    <li>Aetna's negotiated US rates protect you from full-price billing</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>vs Cigna and GeoBlue</h3>
  <p>
    All three major US expat insurers (Aetna, Cigna, GeoBlue) offer US coverage for Mexico. The differences:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Aetna:</strong> US included in base price, Aetna US network</li>
    <li><strong>Cigna:</strong> US is an add-on (60-70% premium increase), Cigna US network</li>
    <li><strong>GeoBlue:</strong> US included, Blue Cross Blue Shield network</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <a href="/compare/aetna-international-vs-geoblue">Compare Aetna vs GeoBlue</a> for a detailed breakdown.
  </p>

  <h2 id="mexico-network">Network Coverage in Mexico</h2>
  <p>
    Aetna has a solid network in Mexico, with direct billing at major private hospitals in principal cities and expat destinations.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={hospitalColumns} rows={hospitalRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Coverage by Area</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mexico City:</strong> Excellent coverage at top hospitals (ABC, Médica Sur, Ángeles)</li>
    <li><strong>Guadalajara:</strong> Good coverage—popular with Lake Chapala expats</li>
    <li><strong>Monterrey:</strong> Strong network at Christus Muguerza system</li>
    <li><strong>Beach destinations:</strong> Coverage in Puerto Vallarta, Cancún, Los Cabos</li>
    <li><strong>Smaller towns:</strong> May need to travel to major city or use reimbursement</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Out-of-Network Care</h3>
  <p>
    You can use any licensed provider in Mexico. Pay upfront and submit for reimbursement—Aetna reimburses at their usual, customary, and reasonable (UCR) rates. Mexican healthcare is affordable, so out-of-network care rarely costs more than in-network.
  </p>

  <h2 id="plans-and-pricing">Plans and Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    Aetna offers Pioneer series plans. All include US coverage—no add-on needed.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={planColumns} rows={planRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <em>Prices include worldwide coverage with full US access. USD pricing.</em>
  </p>

  <h3>Plan Recommendations for Mexico</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pioneer:</strong> Hospital-only coverage. Good if you'll use IMSS for routine care and want Aetna for emergencies and US access.</li>
    <li><strong>Pioneer Prime:</strong> The practical choice for most. Includes outpatient, good balance of coverage and cost.</li>
    <li><strong>Pioneer Platinum:</strong> Comprehensive coverage. Best for families or those with ongoing health needs.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Navigator Plans (Modular Option)</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna's Navigator plans let you customize:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Core hospital coverage (required)</li>
    <li>Optional outpatient module</li>
    <li>Optional dental and vision</li>
    <li>Optional maternity</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Navigator can reduce costs if you only need hospital coverage—useful if you're using IMSS for routine care.
  </p>

  <h3>Deductible Strategy</h3>
  <p>
    Mexican healthcare is affordable. Consider:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Doctor visit: $30-60</li>
    <li>Specialist: $50-100</li>
    <li>Lab work: $20-50</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A $1,500-2,500 deductible can significantly reduce premiums while keeping exposure manageable.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Built-In US Coverage"
    description="No surprise premiums when visiting family or needing US care."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/aetna-international"
  />

  <h2 id="vs-local-options">vs Mexican Insurers</h2>
  <p>
    How does Aetna International compare to Mexican insurance companies?
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Key Differences</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Deductible structure:</strong> Mexican insurers use per-illness lifetime deductibles. You pay the deductible once per condition, forever. Aetna uses annual deductibles that reset each year.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>US coverage:</strong> Mexican insurers don't cover the US. If you visit the US at all, you'd need separate travel insurance—or pay out of pocket.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Medical evacuation:</strong> Aetna includes evacuation to the US or another country. Mexican insurers typically don't include this.
  </p>

  <h2 id="imss-combo">IMSS + Aetna Strategy</h2>
  <p>
    Many savvy expats use both IMSS and Aetna International. Here's why it works:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">The Combination Approach</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
      <li><strong>IMSS ($500/year):</strong> Routine care, prescriptions, basic coverage</li>
      <li><strong>Aetna Pioneer ($130/mo):</strong> Private hospitals, US access, emergencies</li>
      <li><strong>Total: ~$275/month</strong> for comprehensive Mexico + US coverage</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h3>When to Use Each</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>IMSS:</strong> Routine care, generic medications, basic checkups</li>
    <li><strong>Aetna:</strong> Private hospitals, English-speaking doctors, US trips, emergencies, specialists</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    IMSS is affordable enough (~$40/month for under-60s) that it makes sense as a backup and for routine care, even if you have Aetna.
  </p>

  <h2 id="who-its-for">Who Should Choose Aetna</h2>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Ideal For</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
        <li>US citizens and retirees</li>
        <li>Those who visit the US regularly</li>
        <li>People with US doctors or specialists</li>
        <li>Expats who might repatriate</li>
        <li>Those wanting Medicare replacement abroad</li>
        <li>Families needing comprehensive coverage</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Consider Alternatives</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Non-US expats (no US benefit)</li>
        <li>Budget-focused (IMSS + GNP cheaper)</li>
        <li>Those who never visit the US</li>
        <li>Expats wanting largest Mexican network</li>
        <li>Those preferring peso billing</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <h3>Does Aetna International replace Medicare?</h3>
  <p>
    Aetna provides coverage abroad that Medicare doesn't offer. For US expats in Mexico, it effectively replaces Medicare for your healthcare needs. Many expats keep Medicare Part A (hospital, which is free) as a backup if they return to the US permanently, but use Aetna for actual day-to-day coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I use Aetna and IMSS together?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Many expats enroll in IMSS (~$500/year) for routine care and basic coverage, then use Aetna for private hospitals, US trips, and major medical situations. It's a cost-effective strategy.
  </p>

  <h3>What if I need surgery—US or Mexico?</h3>
  <p>
    Both are covered. Mexican hospitals are excellent and much cheaper—Aetna covers either. Many expats choose Mexico for elective procedures and reserve US access for complex cases or when they want a second opinion.
  </p>

  <h3>How does Aetna compare to GeoBlue for Mexico?</h3>
  <p>
    Both are excellent for US expats with built-in US coverage. Aetna offers modular Navigator plans; GeoBlue offers the Blue Cross network. Similar pricing and coverage. <a href="/compare/aetna-international-vs-geoblue">See our comparison</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>Is Mexico health insurance tax deductible?</h3>
  <p>
    Possibly. US expats may be able to deduct health insurance premiums depending on their tax situation. Consult a tax professional familiar with expat taxes.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Coverage in Mexico?"
    description="Get a personalized Aetna International quote for your situation."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/aetna-international"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Network availability, pricing, and coverage terms change. We are not insurance brokers. Verify all information with Aetna International before making decisions.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
